Pago 40, l. 2. Facta est turpis pax. The preliminaries were settled at a parliament held at York, in which, on the 1st March, 1328, Edward renounced all claim to superiority.—Foedera, ii. 730. This renunciation is evidently Bake1³s ‘ emtam, cuius tenoris et continencie series communiter ignoratur! The terms os the treaty which followed were: that there should be perpetual peace between the two kingdoms, that David Bruee should marry Edward’s sister, Joan of the Tower, that all deeds touching the subjection of Scotland to England and the stone of Scone should be surrendered, and that Bruce should pay the sum of Aaopoo, ete. The treaty was agreed to by Bruce, 17th March, and ratified by Edward in parliament at Northampton, 4th May, 1328.—Foedera, ii. 734, 741.

Desponsata sorore regie. ‘ Dedit etiam juvenis rex praedictus sororem suam juniorem, dominam Johannem de Turre, in uxorem David filio Roberti de Erus, regis Scotiae, qui puer tunc erat quinque annorum, sicut ordinaverat mater sua, regina Angliae, quae tunc temporis totum regnum regebat. Celebratae vero sunt nuptiae solemniter apud Berwicum, Dominica die proxima ante festum sanctae Mariae Magdalenae [17th July].’—Chr0n. Lanercost, 261. The marriage, as well as the other articles of the treaty, was most unpopular in England: see Murimuth, p. 56, note 11. The princess was born in July, 1321 ; she was thus just seven years of age. The Brute chronicle (Harley MS. 2279) thus refers to the event ε ‘And s0, thurgh hire cursede counsel, pis David spousede, atte Berwyke, dame Johan atte pe Toure, pat was kyng Edwardis suster, as pe geste telleth, uppon Marie Mandeleyn daye [22 JulyJ, the yeer os grace mcccxxviij„ to grcte harme and enpeyryng to alle pe kynges blode pat were os pat gentil ladie come. Alias pe tyme! sor wonder moche was pat fayre damoseil dispergede, sith that she was mariede ayens alle pe comone assente of pe lordes os Engelonde.' David's nickname ‘drite on auter’ is also given, but without explanation. Caxton (Crone’cles os England) prints it ‘dritonantier,’ evidently without understanding the meaning. The Fructus Tempmm has, more correctly, ‘dritonautier.'
